A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 12 Jan 2020
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2021; 34(02) [edited]
https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=37576


African swine fever (ASF), Latvia
---------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 12 Jan 2021 from Dr. Maris Balodis, Chief Veterinary Officer & Director General, Food and Veterinary Service, Ministry of Agriculture, Riga, Latvia

Summary
Report type: follow-up report No 1
Date of start of the event: 1 Jan 2021
Date of confirmation of the event: 1 Jan 2021
Reason for notification: Recurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 30 Dec 2020
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: African swine fever virus
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (advanced), necropsy
This event pertains to the whole country.

New outbreaks (9)
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 9
[The outbreaks reported in the notification occurred between 6 Jan and 8 Jan 2021. The 9 reported outbreaks occurred in the following provinces: Skrundas, Kuldigas, Tukuma, Dagdas, Valkas. The affected species in these outbreaks was wild boar: _Sus scrofa_. See details of the outbreaks in the OIE report at the source URL above. - Mod.CRD]

Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Wild boar: _Sus scrofa_ (Suidae) / - / 10 / 6 / 4 / 0

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Wild boar: _Sus scrofa_ (Suidae) / ** / ** / 60 / **
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter
** Not calculated because of missing information

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Epidemiological comments: African swine fever positive wild boars were hunted within the restricted area listed under the zones of Annex to European Commission Implementing Decision 2014/709/EU.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country; screening; quarantine; official disposal of carcasses, by-products and waste; control of wildlife reservoirs; zoning; disinfection; vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists); no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type:
Institute of Food Safety, Animal Health and Environment, BIOR (National laboratory)
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Wild boar / immunoperoxidase monolayer assay (IPMA) / 6 Jan 2021 / Positive
Wild boar / immunoperoxidase monolayer assay (IPMA) / 8 Jan 2021 / Positive
Wild boar / real-time PCR / 6 Jan 2021 / Positive
Wild boar / real-time PCR / 8 Jan 2021 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[On 8 Jan 2021, Latvia reported 2 outbreaks of ASF located in the provinces of Brocenu and Kraslavas. These outbreaks have affected wild boars. See report at https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?reportid=37503

The most recent update (until 20 Oct 2020) on the epidemiological situation and the measures regarding ASF in Latvia can be found at https://ec.europa.eu/food/sites/food/files/animals/docs/reg-com_ahw_20201020_pres_asf_lva.pdf. - Mod.CRD

